    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-10-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-10-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="372"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d372">
                <head>372. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_CG4" type="from">Gordon
                        Chase</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to the President’s
                    Special Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BMG2"
                        type="to">Bundy</persName>)<note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d372fn0"
                        >Source: Johnson Library, National Security File, Country File, Cuba,
                        Contact with Cuban Leaders, 5/63-4/65. Top Secret; Eyes Only.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-10-21">October 21, 1963</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Accommodation with <persName>Castro</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>As you requested, I spoke to Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_AWH2"
                        >Attwood</persName> in New York about the attached.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d372fn1">Apparent reference to <ref target="#d367">Document
                            367</ref>.</note> He gave the following information. (The conversation
                    was necessarily vague and we didn’t go into much detail.)</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Adlai Stevenson had received approval for the approach.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_AWH2">Attwood</persName> spoke to
                        Lechuga. Lechuga expressed interest (he is a soft-liner) and suggested that
                        someone from our side should go down to Cuba to talk with
                            <persName>Castro</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_AWH2"
                            >Attwood</persName> replied that the <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>
                        wasa more appropriate talking place. Lechuga said he would convey the
                        message to Havana.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AWH2">Attwood</persName> concluded that the ball is in
                        Cuban hands and the door is ajar. However, he is not hopeful. While Lechuga
                        and <persName>Castro</persName>, himself, might be interested, he feels that
                            <persName>Castro</persName> is too well boxed in by such hard-liners as
                        Guevara to be able to maneuver much.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">GC</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
